1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:06,541
Here at VOA Learning English, we love to help teachers.

2
00:00:06,541 --> 00:00:14,883
Our aim is to make learning more interactive, student-centered and fun.

3
00:00:14,883 --> 00:00:29,021
In today’s Education Tips, we offer speaking and writing activities for beginning, intermediate and advanced English learners.

4
00:00:29,021 --> 00:00:43,645
As a teacher who uses the VOA Learning English website, you know about our quizzes, downloadable lesson plans, and other materials.

5
00:00:43,645 --> 00:00:53,912
But, there are other creative and less obvious ways to use our programs in your classroom.

6
00:00:53,912 --> 00:00:59,707
Let’s start with a speaking activity for beginners.

7
00:00:59,707 --> 00:01:09,099
Every day, VOA Learning English posts fascinating photos from around the world.

8
00:01:09,099 --> 00:01:13,187
We call it the Day in Photos.

9
00:01:13,187 --> 00:01:29,563
You can find photos of all kinds of things, such as a fireworks display in Mexico City or a fisherman sitting in his boat in the Egyptian Nile River Delta.

10
00:01:29,563 --> 00:01:39,952
Here’s a speaking activity that will inspire even the shyest beginning speakers to talk to their classmates.

11
00:01:39,952 --> 00:01:49,515
With students sitting in pairs, show the image on the screen, without showing the description.

12
00:01:49,515 --> 00:01:55,419
Have one student describe what she sees in the image.

13
00:01:55,419 --> 00:02:05,699
Then, have the other student imagine what the people or animals in the photo are thinking or saying.

14
00:02:05,699 --> 00:02:16,136
This activity gives learners the chance not just to practice speaking but to use their imaginations.

15
00:02:16,136 --> 00:02:23,555
Our video series are also a great tool for getting students talking.

16
00:02:23,555 --> 00:02:34,829
For example, Learning English TV features two-minute videos on topics from science to politics to health.

17
00:02:34,829 --> 00:02:44,872
For intermediate learners, you can use pair work to have students summarize what they learn watching the videos.

18
00:02:44,872 --> 00:02:53,987
You can play two different videos so both students get the chance to summarize something different.

19
00:02:53,987 --> 00:03:01,317
Then, as a whole class, you can discuss what the students learned from the videos.

20
00:03:01,317 --> 00:03:09,344
Advanced speakers can also get talking by watching Learning English TV.

21
00:03:09,344 --> 00:03:32,200
For this level, have students do the activity exactly as they did in the intermediate activity. But, ask students to come up with three questions on additional things they’d like to learn about the topic.

22
00:03:32,200 --> 00:03:44,245
For advanced speakers, you can also use our video series America’s Presidents to spark discussion on debatable topics.

23
00:03:44,245 --> 00:03:53,448
Students can work in small groups to express their opinions on what they watched in the video.

24
00:03:53,448 --> 00:04:07,187
For example, John Adams, America’s second president, made policies about immigrants that became controversial during his time.

25
00:04:07,187 --> 00:04:19,373
English in a Minute and English at the Movies are also great for sparking lively conversation among advanced English learners.

26
00:04:19,373 --> 00:04:25,949
These short series explore an idiom, or common expression.

27
00:04:25,949 --> 00:04:35,045
For example, in one English at the Movies episode, the expression "fresh start" is explored.

28
00:04:35,045 --> 00:04:43,688
A young man and his mother move to a new place, and the mother says, "Fresh start."

29
00:04:43,688 --> 00:04:59,067
Students can use the context of the movie clip and its explanation – based on the multiple choice quiz in the video – to develop their understanding of the expression.

30
00:04:59,067 --> 00:05:10,387
One fun activity is to have students create two- or three-person dialogues using the new idioms.

31
00:05:10,387 --> 00:05:20,843
They can act out or voice the dialogues in their groups, then move around and share them with other groups.

32
00:05:20,843 --> 00:05:26,813
Or, they can share the dialogues with the whole class.

33
00:05:26,813 --> 00:05:33,045
You can use the Day in Photos series for writing, too.

34
00:05:33,045 --> 00:05:45,069
Before doing this activity, choose a photo or a few photos to display on the screen, without the descriptions.

35
00:05:45,069 --> 00:05:52,909
Tell students they will write a story about the person or people in the photo.

36
00:05:52,909 --> 00:06:12,691
If the students need help using their imaginations, provide a list of questions on the board or a shared screen, such as: What are they doing in the photo and why? What are they thinking in the photo?

37
00:06:12,691 --> 00:06:20,560
Another great way to get beginning learners writing is our Let’s Learn English series.

38
00:06:20,560 --> 00:06:27,629
Each lesson asks learners to write a response to the topic of the lesson.

39
00:06:27,629 --> 00:06:37,301
For example, Lesson 25 shows the main character, Anna, learning about a new video game.

40
00:06:37,301 --> 00:06:45,787
Learners are asked to write an answer to this question: What games do you like to play?

41
00:06:45,787 --> 00:06:53,573
Use our videos to also get your intermediate learners excited about writing.

42
00:06:53,573 --> 00:07:01,747
News Words is a series featuring short videos about popular words in the news.

43
00:07:01,747 --> 00:07:12,027
For this intermediate writing activity, choose a video that features a word relevant to most of your students.

44
00:07:12,027 --> 00:07:31,499
For example, the video News Words: Sacred talks about two uses of the word: one is in reference to something that deserves great respect, and the other is about religious or holy topics.

45
00:07:31,499 --> 00:07:39,203
Many students may be able to relate to the idea of something being sacred.

46
00:07:39,203 --> 00:07:49,307
For this activity, students watch the video and then write a paragraph about the importance of the word for them.

47
00:07:49,307 --> 00:07:56,496
They sit in pairs or small groups and share their writing with one another.

48
00:07:56,496 --> 00:08:06,461
The series Words and Their Stories explores common expressions in American English.

49
00:08:06,461 --> 00:08:18,320
Each story contains many idioms, or expressions, usually with a mysterious or exciting storyline.

50
00:08:18,320 --> 00:08:33,611
For example, “Mystery at the Ice Castle Inn” told the story of four strangers stuck at a faraway inn on a mountain during an ice storm.

51
00:08:33,611 --> 00:08:41,957
All the idioms in the story are related to ice, snow or cold.

52
00:08:41,957 --> 00:08:53,261
Words and Their Stories is good for advanced writing activities because students get to practice using many idioms.

53
00:08:53,261 --> 00:09:02,099
For this activity, students work in pairs or small groups, depending on class size.

54
00:09:02,099 --> 00:09:08,861
Play the audio as the students view the text on a shared screen.

55
00:09:08,861 --> 00:09:18,184
Students then discuss the idioms in the story to make sure they fully understand the meanings.

56
00:09:18,184 --> 00:09:23,949
Together, they then write sentences for each idiom.

57
00:09:23,949 --> 00:09:31,008
After they’re finished, you can ask for examples from each group.

58
00:09:31,008 --> 00:09:38,469
Before doing any of the activities, decide on your method of feedback.

59
00:09:38,469 --> 00:09:47,221
A good feedback method for speaking activities is for you to monitor students as they speak.

60
00:09:47,221 --> 00:09:54,811
Take notes on some of the phrases you hear, whether they are correct or incorrect.

61
00:09:54,811 --> 00:10:01,947
After the activity, write the phrases on the board or shared screen.

62
00:10:01,947 --> 00:10:06,971
Then, ask students whether the grammar is correct.

63
00:10:06,971 --> 00:10:16,312
If students agree that the phrase is already correct, have the class simply repeat the phrase aloud.

64
00:10:16,312 --> 00:10:26,275
If it’s incorrect, ask for corrections. You can have volunteers make the corrections on the board.

65
00:10:26,275 --> 00:10:36,469
For giving writing feedback, we recommend that you also keep things interactive.

66
00:10:36,469 --> 00:10:47,680
Put a checklist of questions on the board and then have students correct each other’s writing based on the questions.

67
00:10:47,680 --> 00:11:11,848
The checklist can include questions such as: Is the main point clear? Did the details support the main point? Is the punctuation correct? Are the sentences complete? Does the writer use correct grammar?

68
00:11:11,848 --> 00:11:23,237
You can also go around and monitor to make sure students are giving one another accurate corrections.

69
00:11:23,237 --> 00:11:30,904
Stay tuned for more Education Tips stories in the coming weeks.

70
00:11:30,904 --> 00:11:36,168
I'm Alice Bryant. And I'm John Russell.